'''Poya Bay''' or '''Baie de la Poya''', also known as '''Porwi Bay''', is a bay of [[New Caledonia]].<ref name="UNU">{{cite web|url=http://www.greenstone.org/greenstone3/nzdl;jsessionid=9C07FFA7400A6C3C823F1ACAF98A3D9D?a=d&d=HASH01e0de34b153f45530bc1736.5.pp&c=ccgi&sib=1&dt=&ec=&et=&p.a=b&p.s=ClassifierBrowse&p.sa=|title=The impacts of opencast mining in New Caledonia|publisher=The United Nations University|accessdate=9 June 2011}}</ref>
It "lies about 2 miles west-northwestward of [[Cape Goulvain]], 2 miles in length, and is entered by Poya Passage, a narrow channel between the reefs, about 800 yards wide."<ref name="Office1928">{{cite book|author=United States. Hydrographic Office|title=Pacific islands pilot|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=_1EPAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=10 June 2011|year=1928|publisher=U.S. Govt. Print. Off.}}</ref><ref name="Office1952">{{cite book|author=United States. Hydrographic Office|title=Sailing directions for the Pacific islands|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=iAQOAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=10 June 2011|year=1952|publisher=G.P.O.}}</ref> The mouth of the [[Poya River]] is located on the bay.

